What I would suggest is to design your graphics using a vector graphics editor like Inkscape (free).

Then you can open the resulting SVG file in your favorite text editor and save snippets of the file as strings to insert into your own file:
For example, here is a part of a file for drawing a circle:
```svg
  &lt;g
     inkscape:label=&quot;Layer 1&quot;
     inkscape:groupmode=&quot;layer&quot;
     id=&quot;layer1&quot;&gt;
    &lt;circle 
       style=&quot;opacity:0.1;fill:#008000;fill-opacity:1;stroke:#000000;stroke-width:0.26458332;stroke-opacity:1&quot;
       id=&quot;path10&quot;
       cx=&quot;43.534008&quot;
       cy=&quot;32.312469&quot;
       r=&quot;18.520834&quot; /&gt;    
  &lt;/g&gt;
```
I would also get rid of extraneous information, such as the `inkscape:label` and `inkscape:groupmode` which you don&#39;t need, and especially the `id=` since you want to reuse the code. Then save pieces of this in static strings (or better in a array or structure):
```c++
    const string circleS0 = &quot;&lt;g id=\&quot;circle1\&quot;&gt;&lt;circle style=\&quot;opacity:0.1;fill:#008000;fill-opacity:1;stroke:#000000;stroke-width:0.26458332;stroke-opacity:1\&quot; id=\&quot;path10\&quot; cx=\&quot;&quot;;
    const string circleS1 = &quot;\&quot; cy=\&quot;&quot;;
    const string circleS2 = &quot;\&quot;  r=\&quot;&quot;;
    const string circleS3 = &quot;\&quot; /&gt; &lt;/g&gt;&quot;;
```
**IMPORTANT NOTE:** SVG format _requires_ a lot of double-quotes which unfortunately have to be escaped in C++ (as I did above).
 
Now you create some variables that contain the things that make this a unique circle that you can draw where you want:
```c++
    string circleX = &quot;43.534008&quot;;
    string circleY = &quot;32.312469&quot;;
    string circleR = &quot;18.520834&quot;;
```
Finally, you need to output all the pieces in order, but I&#39;ll leave that to your C++ skills.

This example might seem overwhelming without a library, but I did it for creating electrical cable assembly drawings and text grids (Bills of Materials) and it was not hard at all. I even include the customer&#39;s logo in the title block of the drawings thanks to embedded graphics.

IIRC, the format specification mini-language can access attributes of objects, but it can&#39;t call methods. It assumes you&#39;re looking for an attribute with the name &quot;lower()&quot;, parentheses included.

Does `value` have to be a string? Perhaps you could create a string subclass with a `@property` that returns a lowercased version of itself. For example:

    class StringEx(str):
        @property
        def lowercase(self):
            return self.lower()
    
    x = StringEx(&quot;Hello, World!&quot;)
    s = &quot;Lowercase: {value.lowercase}&quot;
    print(s.format(value=x))

Result:

    Lowercase: hello, world!

-------

If you expect to have a lot of different format strings and don&#39;t want to implement a property for each string method, you can cover all the zero-argument methods in one go by overriding `__getattr__`:

    class StringEx(str):
        def __getattr__(self, name):
            if name.endswith(&quot;()&quot;):
                return getattr(self, name[:-2])()
            else:
                raise AttributeError
    
    x = StringEx(&quot;HeLlO, WoRlD!&quot;)
    format_strings = [
        &quot;Regular: {value}&quot;,
        &quot;Lowercase: {value.lower()}&quot;,
        &quot;Uppercase: {value.upper()}&quot;,
        &quot;Title: {value.title()}&quot;
    ]
    
    for s in format_strings:
        print(s.format(value=x))

Result:

    Regular: HeLlO, WoRlD!
    Lowercase: hello, world!
    Uppercase: HELLO, WORLD!
    Title: Hello, World!

