From [MDN Docs][1] here 

&gt; Property names must be strings. This means that non-string objects cannot be used as keys in the object. Any non-string object, including a number, is typecasted into a string via the toString method.

So, basically the keys are type coerced to strings even if they are numbers.

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    const object = { 21 : &#39;test&#39;, &#39;21&#39;: &#39;message&#39; };

    console.log(object)

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;



  [1]: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Object

The relevant bits of the standard are

&gt; [12.3.2.1 Runtime Semantics:
&gt; Evaluation](http://www.ecma-international.org/ecma-262/8.0/#sec-property-accessors-runtime-semantics-evaluation)
&gt; 
&gt; MemberExpression:MemberExpression[Expression]
&gt; 
&gt; ...6. Let propertyKey be ? ToPropertyKey(propertyNameValue).

and
 
&gt; [7.1.14 ToPropertyKey ( argument )](http://www.ecma-international.org/ecma-262/8.0/#sec-topropertykey)
&gt; 
&gt; 1. Let key be ? ToPrimitive(argument, hint String).
&gt; 
&gt; 2. If Type(key) is Symbol, then Return key.
&gt; 
&gt; 3. Return ! ToString(key).

In plain English, in `object[whatever]`, `whatever` is converted to a string, unless it&#39;s a `symbol`.

Illustration:

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    let s = Symbol();

    let o = { 
      &#39;12&#39;: 1,
      &#39;foo&#39;: 2,
      &#39;true&#39;: 3,
      [s]: 4
    }

    console.log(o[6*2])
    console.log(o[{toString: () =&gt; &#39;foo&#39;}])
    console.log(o[1 === 1])
    console.log(o[s])

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

The behaviour of object initializers is described in [12.2.6.7](http://www.ecma-international.org/ecma-262/8.0/#sec-object-initializer-runtime-semantics-evaluation) and is exactly the same.

